04722nam a2200685Ia 9781442673571DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t19941994onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013944150  a97814426735717 a10.3138/97814426735712doi  a(DE-B1597)464373  a(OCoLC)944178310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR3596b.E83 1994 7aLAN0090302bisacsh04a821.0092201 aEsterhammer, Angela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreating States :bStudies in the Performative Language of John Milton and William Blake /cAngela Esterhammer. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (245 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tReferences and Abbreviations -- tPrologue: Words, Worlds, Acts, and Visions -- t1. Performative Language and Visionary Poetry -- t2. Speech Acts and World-Creation -- t3. The Language of Inspiration in Milton's Prose -- t4. Paradise Lost: The Creation of Poetry and the Poetry of Creation -- t5. The Circumference of Vision: Songs of Innocence and of Experience -- t6. Binding the Infinite: Blake's Brief Epics -- t7. Blake's Jerusalem: Statements and States -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the concept of the performative has influenced literary theory in numerous ways, this book represents one of the first full-length studies of performative language in literary texts. Creating States examines the visionary poetry of John Milton and William Blake, using a critical approach based on principles of speech-act theory as articulated by J.L. Austin, John Searle, and Emile Benveniste. Angela Esterhammer proposes a new way of understanding the relationship between these two poets, while at the same time evaluating the role of speech-act philosophy in the reading of visionary poetry and Romantic literature. Esterhammer distinguishes between the 'sociopolitical performative,' the speech act which is defined by a societal context and derives power from institutional authority, and the `phenomenological performative,' language which is invested with the power to posit or create because of the individual will and consciousness of the speaker. Analysing texts such as The Reason of Church-Government, Paradise Lost, The Marriage of Heaven and Hell, and Jerusalem, Esterhammer traces the parallel evolution of Milton and Blake from writers of political and anti-prelatical tracts to poets who, having failed in their attempts to alter historical circumstances through a direct address to their contemporaries, reaffirm their faith in individual visionary consciousness and the creative word – while continuing to use the forms of a socially or politically performative language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnglish languagexVersification. 0aEnglish languageyEarly modern, 1500-1700xStyle. 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aVisions in literature. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Pragmatics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267357140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442673571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442673571/original  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL